I have an attachment picture (screenshot) that I want to include in my description. I use {noformat}!screenshot-1.jpg|thumbnail!{noformat}. 

So far so good, the thumbnail shows up. 

However, when I click on the thumbnail the picture opens up in a new tab/window instead of the gallery view you get when you click on the attachment thumbnail in the attachments area.

I would like that the wiki image include would generate code that will show the gallery instead of what it does now.

So from *old*:
{code:html}
<a id="10670_thumb" href="/secure/attachment/10670/10670_screenshot-1.jpg" title="screenshot-1.jpg">
<img src="/secure/thumbnail/10670/10670_10670_screenshot-1.jpg" align="absmiddle" border="0" />
</a>
{code}

to *this*:
{code:html}
<a class="gallery" rel="gallery" href="/secure/attachment/10670/screenshot-1.jpg" title="screenshot-1.jpg - Latest 2010/08/27 11:43 - Jira Administrator">
<img src="/secure/thumbnail/10670/10670_screenshot-1.jpg" width="200" height="150" alt="" />
</a>
{code}

*Steps to Reproduce:*
1. Create a shared filter having similar JQL:
{noformat:borderStyle=dashed| borderColor=#6A8EB3 |bgColor=#F8F8F8}
project in (PROJECT1, PROJECT2)
{noformat}

2. Execute the shared filter with a user that does not have browse permissions for project PROJECT1 (he/she can be the owner of the filter). The resulting JQL becomes:

*Expected Results:*
The filter would run normally, returning only issues in which the user running it has the necessary permissions - in this case, it would return all issues from PROJECT2.

*Actual Results:*
The filter becomes:
{noformat:borderStyle=dashed| borderColor=#6A8EB3 |bgColor=#F8F8F8}
project in (10020, PROJECT2)
{noformat}
* The non-viewable projects ID is replaced with numeric ID.

* The filter initially displays the results, but once switching to Edit no results return with the displayed error message:
{quote}
A value with ID '10020' does not exist for the field 'project'.
{quote}

* If the filter is used in a gadget, the gadget displays the message below and doesn't display any results:
{quote}The selected filter filter-10100 has an error: A value with ID '10100' does not exist for the field 'project'..{quote}

As some of the database has a case-sensitive identifiers (column header names), upgrading JIRA version is impossible. When performing XML export, JIRA use lower and uppercase SQL query randomly causing error to the case-sensitive database (eg. Sybase ASE):
{noformat}
Error occurred during export before upgrade: Error in action: com.atlassian.jira.action.admin.DataExport@634ae081, result: error Error exporting data: org.ofbiz.core.entity.GenericDataSourceException: SQL Exception while executing the following:SELECT ID, USERNAME, PAGENAME, DESCRIPTION, SEQUENCE, FAV_COUNT, LAYOUT, ppversion FROM portalpage (Invalid column name 'ID'. ) 
{noformat}
From the above error during the XML export, JIRA use SQL query with the uppercase column name 'ID'. Although the table is changed to have a uppercase column name 'ID', the below error is generated with invalid column name 'id':
{noformat}
2010-09-13 10:22:58 error Exception thrown during upgrade: org.ofbiz.core.entity.GenericDataSourceException: SQL Exception while executing the following:UPDATE portalpage SET ppversion = ? WHERE id = ? (Invalid column name 'id'. ) com.atlassian.jira.exception.DataAccessException: org.ofbiz.core.entity.GenericDataSourceException: SQL Exception while executing the following:UPDATE portalpage SET ppversion = ? WHERE id = ? (Invalid column name 'id'. ) 
{noformat}
JIRA should have a standardized SQL query so that case-sensitive database (eg. Sybase ASE) will be compatible with JIRA also

